result.execSummary:
The defendant Amy K Jung was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Theft-Movable Property <=$2500, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Amy K Jung in court with attorney Tara L. Teesch. Colleen Catherine Nordin appeared for the State of Wisconsin. State moves to amend charge to misdemeanor Theft, advises of sentencing recommendation. Defense provides element sheet for amended charge. Court accepts plea previously entered, finds Defendant guilty of amended charge. State/Defense make joint sentencing recommendations. Bond no longer in effect.

Defendant Amy K Jung in court with attorney Peter Raymond Heyne. Joan M. Korb appeared for the State of Wisconsin. State advises that Defendant will be entering plea to original charge, requests that Court withhold judgment of conviction to give Defendant 4 months to pay restitution and surcharge, and if completed, charge will be amended to misdemeanor and elements reviewed at sentencing. Court reviews charge, max. penalties, elements. Defendant enters guilty plea. Court questions Defendant on rights, finds plea made freely and voluntarily and withholds acceptance of plea.  Court reviews collateral consequences of felony conviction, possible penalties. Bond continues as is.  Sentencing hearing scheduled for August 24, 2017 at 11:00 am.
